 0019:     """The famous *SVD* algorithm, as popularized by `Simon Funk
 0020:     <http://sifter.org/~simon/journal/20061211.html>`_ during the Netflix
 0021:     Prize. When baselines are not used, this is equivalent to Probabilistic
 0022:     Matrix Factorization :cite:`salakhutdinov2008a` (see :ref:`note
 0023:     <unbiased_note>` below).
 0024: 
 0025:     The prediction :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 0026: 
 0027:     .. math::
 0028:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^Tp_u
 0029: 
 0030:     If user :math:`u` is unknown, then the bias :math:`b_u` and the factors
 0031:     :math:`p_u` are assumed to be zero. The same applies for item :math:`i`
 0032:     with :math:`b_i` and :math:`q_i`.
 0033: 
 0034:     For details, see equation (5) from :cite:`Koren:2009`. See also
 0035:     :cite:`Ricci:2010`, section 5.3.1.
 0036: 
 0037:     To estimate all the unknown, we minimize the following regularized squared
 0038:     error:
 0039: 
 0040:     .. math::
 0041:         \sum_{r_{ui} \in R_{train}} \left(r_{ui} - \hat{r}_{ui} \\right)^2 +
 0042:         \lambda\\left(b_i^2 + b_u^2 + ||q_i||^2 + ||p_u||^2\\right)
 0043: 
 0044: 
 0045:     The minimization is performed by a very straightforward stochastic gradient
 0046:     descent:
 0047: 
 0048:     .. math::
 0049:         b_u &\\leftarrow b_u &+ \gamma (e_{ui} - \lambda b_u)\\\\
 0050:         b_i &\\leftarrow b_i &+ \gamma (e_{ui} - \lambda b_i)\\\\
 0051:         p_u &\\leftarrow p_u &+ \gamma (e_{ui} \\cdot q_i - \lambda p_u)\\\\
 0052:         q_i &\\leftarrow q_i &+ \gamma (e_{ui} \\cdot p_u - \lambda q_i)
 0053: 
 0054:     where :math:`e_{ui} = r_{ui} - \\hat{r}_{ui}`. These steps are performed
 0055:     over all the ratings of the trainset and repeated ``n_epochs`` times.
 0056:     Baselines are initialized to ``0``. User and item factors are randomly
 0057:     initialized according to a normal distribution, which can be tuned using
 0058:     the ``init_mean`` and ``init_std_dev`` parameters.
 0059: 
 0060:     You also have control over the learning rate :math:`\gamma` and the
 0061:     regularization term :math:`\lambda`. Both can be different for each
 0062:     kind of parameter (see below). By default, learning rates are set to
 0063:     ``0.005`` and regularization terms are set to ``0.02``.
 0064: 
 0065:     .. _unbiased_note:
 0066: 
 0067:     .. note::
 0068:         You can choose to use an unbiased version of this algorithm, simply
 0069:         predicting:
 0070: 
 0071:         .. math::
 0072:             \hat{r}_{ui} = q_i^Tp_u
 0073: 
 0074:         This is equivalent to Probabilistic Matrix Factorization
 0075:         (:cite:`salakhutdinov2008a`, section 2) and can be achieved by setting
 0076:         the ``biased`` parameter to ``False``.
 0077: 
 0078: 
 0079:     Args:
 0080:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``100``.
 0081:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 0082:             ``20``.
 0083:         biased(bool): Whether to use baselines (or biases). See :ref:`note
 0084:             <unbiased_note>` above.  Default is ``True``.
 0085:         init_mean: The mean of the normal distribution for factor vectors
 0086:             initialization. Default is ``0``.
 0087:         init_std_dev: The standard deviation of the normal distribution for
 0088:             factor vectors initialization. Default is ``0.1``.
 0089:         lr_all: The learning rate for all parameters. Default is ``0.005``.
 0090:         reg_all: The regularization term for all parameters. Default is
 0091:             ``0.02``.
 0092:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence over
 0093:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0094:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence over
 0095:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0096:         lr_pu: The learning rate for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence over
 0097:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0098:         lr_qi: The learning rate for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence over
 0099:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0100:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence
 0101:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0102:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence
 0103:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0104:         reg_pu: The regularization term for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence
 0105:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0106:         reg_qi: The regularization term for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence
 0107:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0108:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 0109:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 0110:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 0111:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 0112:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 0113:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 0114:             ``None``.
 0115:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 0116: 
 0117:     Attributes:
 0118:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 0119:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0120:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 0121:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0122:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 0123:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0124:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only
 0125:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0126:     """
 0127:

 0160: 
 0161:         # OK, let's breath. I've seen so many different implementation of this
 0162:         # algorithm that I just not sure anymore of what it should do. I've
 0163:         # implemented the version as described in the BellKor papers (RS
 0164:         # Handbook, etc.). Mymedialite also does it this way. In his post
 0165:         # however, Funk seems to implicitly say that the algo looks like this
 0166:         # (see reg below):
 0167:         # for f in range(n_factors):
 0168:         #       for _ in range(n_iter):
 0169:         #           for u, i, r in all_ratings:
 0170:         #               err = r_ui - <p[u, :f+1], q[i, :f+1]>
 0171:         #               update p[u, f]
 0172:         #               update q[i, f]
 0173:         # which is also the way https://github.com/aaw/IncrementalSVD.jl
 0174:         # implemented it.
 0175:         #
 0176:         # Funk: "Anyway, this will train one feature (aspect), and in
 0177:         # particular will find the most prominent feature remaining (the one
 0178:         # that will most reduce the error that's left over after previously
 0179:         # trained features have done their best). When it's as good as it's
 0180:         # going to get, shift it onto the pile of done features, and start a
 0181:         # new one. For efficiency's sake, cache the residuals (all 100 million
 0182:         # of them) so when you're training feature 72 you don't have to wait
 0183:         # for predictRating() to re-compute the contributions of the previous
 0184:         # 71 features. You will need 2 Gig of ram, a C compiler, and good
 0185:         # programming habits to do this."
 0186: 
 0187:         # A note on cythonization: I haven't dived into the details, but
 0188:         # accessing 2D arrays like pu using just one of the indices like pu[u]
 0189:         # is not efficient. That's why the old (cleaner) version can't be used
 0190:         # anymore, we need to compute the dot products by hand, and update
 0191:         # user and items factors by iterating over all factors...
 0192: 
 0193:         # user biases
 0194:         cdef np.ndarray[np.double_t] bu
 0195:         # item biases
 0196:         cdef np.ndarray[np.double_t] bi
 0197:         # user factors
 0198:         cdef np.ndarray[np.double_t, ndim=2] pu
 0199:         # item factors
 0200:         cdef np.ndarray[np.double_t, ndim=2] qi
 0201:

 0203:         cdef double r, err, dot, puf, qif

 0284:     """The *SVD++* algorithm, an extension of :class:`SVD` taking into account
 0285:     implicit ratings.
 0286: 
 0287:     The prediction :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 0288: 
 0289:     .. math::
 0290:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^T\\left(p_u +
 0291:         |I_u|^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \sum_{j \\in I_u}y_j\\right)
 0292: 
 0293:     Where the :math:`y_j` terms are a new set of item factors that capture
 0294:     implicit ratings. Here, an implicit rating describes the fact that a user
 0295:     :math:`u` rated an item :math:`j`, regardless of the rating value.
 0296: 
 0297:     If user :math:`u` is unknown, then the bias :math:`b_u` and the factors
 0298:     :math:`p_u` are assumed to be zero. The same applies for item :math:`i`
 0299:     with :math:`b_i`, :math:`q_i` and :math:`y_i`.
 0300: 
 0301: 
 0302:     For details, see section 4 of :cite:`Koren:2008:FMN`. See also
 0303:     :cite:`Ricci:2010`, section 5.3.1.
 0304: 
 0305:     Just as for :class:`SVD`, the parameters are learned using a SGD on the
 0306:     regularized squared error objective.
 0307: 
 0308:     Baselines are initialized to ``0``. User and item factors are randomly
 0309:     initialized according to a normal distribution, which can be tuned using
 0310:     the ``init_mean`` and ``init_std_dev`` parameters.
 0311: 
 0312:     You have control over the learning rate :math:`\gamma` and the
 0313:     regularization term :math:`\lambda`. Both can be different for each
 0314:     kind of parameter (see below). By default, learning rates are set to
 0315:     ``0.005`` and regularization terms are set to ``0.02``.
 0316: 
 0317:     Args:
 0318:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``20``.
 0319:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 0320:             ``20``.
 0321:         init_mean: The mean of the normal distribution for factor vectors
 0322:             initialization. Default is ``0``.
 0323:         init_std_dev: The standard deviation of the normal distribution for
 0324:             factor vectors initialization. Default is ``0.1``.
 0325:         lr_all: The learning rate for all parameters. Default is ``0.007``.
 0326:         reg_all: The regularization term for all parameters. Default is
 0327:             ``0.02``.
 0328:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence over
 0329:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0330:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence over
 0331:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0332:         lr_pu: The learning rate for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence over
 0333:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0334:         lr_qi: The learning rate for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence over
 0335:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0336:         lr_yj: The learning rate for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence over
 0337:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0338:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence
 0339:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0340:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence
 0341:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0342:         reg_pu: The regularization term for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence
 0343:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0344:         reg_qi: The regularization term for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence
 0345:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0346:         reg_yj: The regularization term for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence
 0347:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0348:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 0349:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 0350:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 0351:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 0352:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 0353:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 0354:             ``None``.
 0355:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 0356: 
 0357:     Attributes:
 0358:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 0359:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0360:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 0361:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0362:         yj(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The (implicit) item
 0363:             factors (only exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0364:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 0365:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0366:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only
 0367:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0368:     """
 0369:

 0546:     """A collaborative filtering algorithm based on Non-negative Matrix
 0547:     Factorization.
 0548: 
 0549:     This algorithm is very similar to :class:`SVD`. The prediction
 0550:     :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 0551: 
 0552:     .. math::
 0553:         \hat{r}_{ui} = q_i^Tp_u,
 0554: 
 0555:     where user and item factors are kept **positive**. Our implementation
 0556:     follows that suggested in :cite:`NMF:2014`, which is equivalent to
 0557:     :cite:`Zhang96` in its non-regularized form. Both are direct applications
 0558:     of NMF for dense matrices :cite:`NMF_algo`.
 0559: 
 0560:     The optimization procedure is a (regularized) stochastic gradient descent
 0561:     with a specific choice of step size that ensures non-negativity of factors,
 0562:     provided that their initial values are also positive.
 0563: 
 0564:     At each step of the SGD procedure, the factors :math:`f` or user :math:`u`
 0565:     and item :math:`i` are updated as follows:
 0566: 
 0567:     .. math::
 0568:         p_{uf} &\\leftarrow p_{uf} &\cdot \\frac{\\sum_{i \in I_u} q_{if}
 0569:         \\cdot r_{ui}}{\\sum_{i \in I_u} q_{if} \\cdot \\hat{r_{ui}} +
 0570:         \\lambda_u |I_u| p_{uf}}\\\\
 0571:         q_{if} &\\leftarrow q_{if} &\cdot \\frac{\\sum_{u \in U_i} p_{uf}
 0572:         \\cdot r_{ui}}{\\sum_{u \in U_i} p_{uf} \\cdot \\hat{r_{ui}} +
 0573:         \lambda_i |U_i| q_{if}}\\\\
 0574: 
 0575:     where :math:`\lambda_u` and :math:`\lambda_i` are regularization
 0576:     parameters.
 0577: 
 0578:     This algorithm is highly dependent on initial values. User and item factors
 0579:     are uniformly initialized between ``init_low`` and ``init_high``. Change
 0580:     them at your own risks!
 0581: 
 0582:     A biased version is available by setting the ``biased`` parameter to
 0583:     ``True``. In this case, the prediction is set as
 0584: 
 0585:     .. math::
 0586:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^Tp_u,
 0587: 
 0588:     still ensuring positive factors. Baselines are optimized in the same way as
 0589:     in the :class:`SVD` algorithm. While yielding better accuracy, the biased
 0590:     version seems highly prone to overfitting so you may want to reduce the
 0591:     number of factors (or increase regularization).
 0592: 
 0593:     Args:
 0594:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``15``.
 0595:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 0596:             ``50``.
 0597:         biased(bool): Whether to use baselines (or biases). Default is
 0598:             ``False``.
 0599:         reg_pu: The regularization term for users :math:`\lambda_u`. Default is
 0600:             ``0.06``.
 0601:         reg_qi: The regularization term for items :math:`\lambda_i`. Default is
 0602:             ``0.06``.
 0603:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Only relevant for
 0604:             biased version. Default is ``0.02``.
 0605:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Only relevant for
 0606:             biased version. Default is ``0.02``.
 0607:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Only relevant for biased
 0608:             version. Default is ``0.005``.
 0609:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Only relevant for biased
 0610:             version. Default is ``0.005``.
 0611:         init_low: Lower bound for random initialization of factors. Must be
 0612:             greater than ``0`` to ensure non-negative factors. Default is
 0613:             ``0``.
 0614:         init_high: Higher bound for random initialization of factors. Default
 0615:             is ``1``.
 0616:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 0617:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 0618:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 0619:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 0620:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 0621:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 0622:             ``None``.
 0623:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 0624: 
 0625:     Attributes:
 0626:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 0627:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0628:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 0629:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0630:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 0631:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0632:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only
 0633:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0634:     """
 0635:

 0785:     """The *SVD++* algorithm, an extension of :class:`SVD` taking into account
 0786:     implicit ratings.
 0787: 
 0788:     The prediction :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 0789: 
 0790:     .. math::
 0791:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^T\\left(p_u +
 0792:         |I_u|^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \sum_{j \\in I_u}y_j\\right)
 0793: 
 0794:     Where the :math:`y_j` terms are a new set of item factors that capture
 0795:     implicit ratings. Here, an implicit rating describes the fact that a user
 0796:     :math:`u` rated an item :math:`j`, regardless of the rating value.
 0797: 
 0798:     If user :math:`u` is unknown, then the bias :math:`b_u` and the factors
 0799:     :math:`p_u` are assumed to be zero. The same applies for item :math:`i`
 0800:     with :math:`b_i`, :math:`q_i` and :math:`y_i`.
 0801: 
 0802: 
 0803:     For details, see section 4 of :cite:`Koren:2008:FMN`. See also
 0804:     :cite:`Ricci:2010`, section 5.3.1.
 0805: 
 0806:     Just as for :class:`SVD`, the parameters are learned using a SGD on the
 0807:     regularized squared error objective.
 0808: 
 0809:     Baselines are initialized to ``0``. User and item factors are randomly
 0810:     initialized according to a normal distribution, which can be tuned using
 0811:     the ``init_mean`` and ``init_std_dev`` parameters.
 0812: 
 0813:     You have control over the learning rate :math:`\gamma` and the
 0814:     regularization term :math:`\lambda`. Both can be different for each
 0815:     kind of parameter (see below). By default, learning rates are set to
 0816:     ``0.005`` and regularization terms are set to ``0.02``.
 0817: 
 0818:     Args:
 0819:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``20``.
 0820:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 0821:             ``20``.
 0822:         init_mean: The mean of the normal distribution for factor vectors
 0823:             initialization. Default is ``0``.
 0824:         init_std_dev: The standard deviation of the normal distribution for
 0825:             factor vectors initialization. Default is ``0.1``.
 0826:         lr_all: The learning rate for all parameters. Default is ``0.007``.
 0827:         reg_all: The regularization term for all parameters. Default is
 0828:             ``0.02``.
 0829:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence over
 0830:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0831:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence over
 0832:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0833:         lr_pu: The learning rate for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence over
 0834:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0835:         lr_qi: The learning rate for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence over
 0836:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0837:         lr_yj: The learning rate for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence over
 0838:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0839:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence
 0840:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0841:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence
 0842:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0843:         reg_pu: The regularization term for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence
 0844:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0845:         reg_qi: The regularization term for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence
 0846:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0847:         reg_yj: The regularization term for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence
 0848:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 0849:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 0850:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 0851:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 0852:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 0853:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 0854:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 0855:             ``None``.
 0856:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 0857: 
 0858:     Attributes:
 0859:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 0860:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0861:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 0862:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0863:         yj(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The (implicit) item
 0864:             factors (only exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0865:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 0866:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0867:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only
 0868:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 0869:     """
 0870:
